The dataset contains maternal health records with:

  • Identifiers: id, provider_id, state
  • Outcome: received_comprehensive_postnatal_care (binary 0/1)
  • Demographics: age, race_ethnicity, edu, self_report_income, dependents
  • Access: insurance, job_type, distance_to_provider
  • Comorbidities (binary): obesity, multiple_gestation, diabetes, heart_disease, placenta_previa, hypertension, gest_hypertension, preeclampsia

Data Preparation

income_levels <- c(
  "$0â$24,999", "$25,000â$49,999", "$50,000â$74,999", "$75,000â$99,999",
  "$100,000â$124,999", "$125,000â$149,999", "$150,000â$174,999", "$175,000+"
)

edu_levels <- c("less_than_hs", "hs", "some_college", "college", "post_grad")
edu_labels <- c("Less than HS", "High School", "Some College", "College", "Post-Grad")

df <- df |>
  mutate(
    postnatal_care = factor(received_comprehensive_postnatal_care,
                            levels = c(0, 1), labels = c("No", "Yes")),
    self_report_income = factor(self_report_income, levels = income_levels, ordered = TRUE),
    edu = factor(edu, levels = edu_levels, labels = edu_labels, ordered = TRUE),
    race_ethnicity = factor(race_ethnicity),
    insurance = factor(insurance, levels = c("no_insurance", "state_provided", "private")),
    job_type = factor(job_type),
    across(c(obesity, multiple_gestation, diabetes, heart_disease,
             placenta_previa, hypertension, gest_hypertension, preeclampsia),
           as.integer)
  )

Modeling Strategy

The primary outcome â received_comprehensive_postnatal_care â is binary (0/1). This calls for logistic regression, the standard approach for binary outcomes. Logistic regression models the log-odds of the outcome as a linear function of predictors and produces odds ratios that are straightforward to interpret.

We include demographic, socioeconomic, access, and comorbidity predictors. We also create a composite comorbidity_count variable (sum of the 8 binary indicators) as a parsimonious way to capture overall health burden.

df <- df |>
  mutate(
    comorbidity_count = obesity + multiple_gestation + diabetes + heart_disease +
      placenta_previa + hypertension + gest_hypertension + preeclampsia
  )

Fit the Logistic Regression

fit <- glm(
  received_comprehensive_postnatal_care ~ age + self_report_income + edu +
    race_ethnicity + insurance + job_type + dependents +
    distance_to_provider + comorbidity_count,
  data = df,
  family = binomial(link = "logit")
)

diag_df <- tibble(
  fitted_prob = fitted(fit),
  deviance_resid = residuals(fit, type = "deviance"),
  pearson_resid = residuals(fit, type = "pearson")
)

Binned Residual Plot

A more informative diagnostic for binary outcomes â average residuals within bins of fitted values should hover near zero.

n_bins <- 40
binned <- diag_df |>
  mutate(bin = ntile(fitted_prob, n_bins)) |>
  group_by(bin) |>
  summarise(
    avg_fitted = mean(fitted_prob),
    avg_resid = mean(pearson_resid),
    se = sd(pearson_resid) / sqrt(n()),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

ggplot(binned, aes(x = avg_fitted, y = avg_resid)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "grey50") +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = -2 * se, ymax = 2 * se), alpha = 0.15, fill = "steelblue") +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(x = "Average Fitted Probability", y = "Average Pearson Residual",
       title = "Binned Residual Plot") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 13)

Interpretation and Caveats

Key findings (associational, not causal):

  • Insurance: Compared to uninsured individuals, those with state-provided or private insurance show different odds of receiving postnatal care.
  • Distance: Greater distance to provider is associated with lower odds of receiving care.
  • Race/ethnicity: Differences across groups are observed, reflecting structural disparities documented in maternal health literature.
  • Comorbidity burden: The composite count captures the cumulative association of health conditions with postnatal care receipt.
  • Income and education: Higher levels of both tend to be associated with higher odds of care receipt.

Limitations:

  1. Observational data â associations do not imply causation. Unmeasured confounders (health literacy, transportation access, provider quality) are likely present.
  2. Clustering â patients are nested within providers and states. Standard errors may be underestimated. A multilevel model (e.g., glmer()) would be more appropriate but was not fit here for simplicity.
  3. Self-reported income â subject to measurement error and reporting bias.
  4. Synthetic data â this dataset is simulated. Findings reflect the data-generating process, not real-world patterns.
  5. No interaction terms â the model assumes additive effects on the log-odds scale. Important interactions (e.g., race Ã insurance) were not explored.
  6. Multiple comparisons â with many predictor levels, some nominally significant results may be spurious.
